## The Halo Continuity Rule

**The Halo Continuity Rule** states that the pavé accent ring must maintain an unbroken, continuous line of diamonds around the entire pear perimeter — from the round shoulder, down both curved sides of the belly, and all the way to the pointed tip. Every gap in the accent ring, every stone that is visibly different in size from its neighbors, and every section where the pavé prongs are visible rather than the stone faces violates The Halo Continuity Rule and creates a visual break in the silhouette.

The tip is where this rule fails most often and most visibly. Setting the halo accent diamonds at the pear's pointed end requires the smallest accent stones in the ring — typically 0.005–0.01ct stones — set precisely to follow the narrowing taper to the point. A less careful bench jeweler will use one slightly larger stone to "cap" the tip rather than maintaining the true tapered-ring effect. The result is a halo that looks fine from a distance but shows a conspicuous single stone at the tip when viewed close-up or in photos. This is the difference between a precision halo and a production halo.

How to identify a Halo Continuity Rule violation before buying: Blue Nile provides 360° video for all diamonds and ring setting renders. When reviewing a pear halo setting, watch the tip at 1:00–1:30 seconds of a standard 360° video rotation — this is when the tip comes closest to the camera. If you can see a gap, a single oversized stone, or an uneven spacing at the point during this rotation, the setting has a continuity issue. The Pavé Diamond Halo Pear by James Allen at $1,555 (91 reviews) has enough buyer-confirmed cases that the tip continuity is verified to be correctly executed — the review count itself is the continuity warranty.

When comparing halo settings, always check the tip detail before the overall design. A halo that looks flawless from above can fail at the tip in close-up. Blue Nile's high-resolution 360° views make this pre-purchase inspection possible without requiring an in-store visit.

