## Single Halo vs. Double Halo for Pear Diamonds

A single halo places one ring of pavé accent diamonds around the pear center. A double halo places two concentric rings — an inner ring that follows the stone's outline closely, and an outer ring that is slightly offset from the first. The double halo adds additional sparkle, increases the overall head size further, and creates a more elaborate, statement-piece aesthetic.

**Single halo** is correct for buyers who want the magnification effect without overwhelm — the center stone remains the clear visual focus, the halo amplifies it, and the ring reads as a single unified piece rather than a collection of elements. Most of the highest-reviewed Blue Nile pear halo settings are single halos. The Pavé Diamond Halo Pear ($1,555, 91 reviews), the Classic Halo ($2,300, 39 reviews), and the Blue Nile Studio Heiress Halo ($3,585, 41 reviews) are all single halo designs.

**Double halo** is correct for buyers who want maximum visual impact, don't mind trading some center-stone focus for overall ring spectacle, and are buying a ring that will be worn for its statement quality as much as for the center diamond. The Blue Nile Studio Double Halo Gala ($5,985, 11 reviews) is the double halo setting in this category. The Sapphire and Diamond Double Halo ($3,535, 14 reviews) adds a second ring of blue sapphires rather than a second diamond ring — this creates a colored contrast layer that frames the pear center with alternating blue and white sparkle. Both are statement-level designs.

The L/W ratio of the center stone matters differently for double halos. In a single halo, the accent ring closely follows the pear's outline — a longer pear reads as longer inside the single halo. In a double halo, the second ring extends the overall head size more uniformly in all directions. A pear with L/W 1.60 inside a double halo may read as slightly more oval-like than teardrop-like because the outer ring's expansion is proportionally greater at the stone's sides than at the tip. Buyers who want the pear silhouette to remain distinctly pear-shaped should lean toward single halos, especially for stones above L/W 1.55.

---

## Hidden Halo vs. Visible Halo

A visible halo (standard halo) is apparent from above — the ring of accent diamonds is set at the same level as or slightly above the center stone's table, creating a crown of diamonds visible from all angles. This is the configuration used by the Pavé Diamond Halo Pear by James Allen and most traditional halo designs.

A hidden halo places the accent diamonds below the center stone's girdle level — tucked under the stone so they are visible only from slightly below the ring face. From directly above, the ring looks like a solitaire. From an angled view, the sparkle of the hidden halo becomes apparent. This is the configuration of the X Split Shank Hidden Halo ($3,040, 3 reviews).

Hidden halos have lower magnification effect than visible halos because the accent diamonds are obscured when the ring is viewed from directly above — the primary viewing angle for engagement rings in normal wear. They add complexity and surprise-sparkle without changing the above-view silhouette. This makes hidden halos appropriate for buyers who want a solitaire look from the front but additional detail when the ring is examined closely.

For pear diamonds specifically, the visible halo is the correct choice in most cases because the pear silhouette is the primary aesthetic purpose of choosing the shape. A hidden halo under a pear stone adds accent diamond value without contributing to the pear shape's visual statement. Buyers who specifically want the minimal above-view look should consider the [Pear Shaped Solitaire Diamond Ring](/pear-shaped-solitaire-diamond-ring) rather than compromising the visible halo's magnification effect.

