## Complete Pricing Guide: Pear Diamond Halo Ring by Budget

**$3,000–$5,000 total — Lab Entry**
A 0.70ct lab-grown pear (F VS2, IGI Excellent, ~$500–$700) + Pavé Diamond Halo Pear by James Allen in 14K rose gold ($1,555) = complete ring from $2,055–$2,255. For 1ct lab-grown pear (F VS2, IGI Excellent, ~$800–$1,100) + same setting = $2,355–$2,655. This is the most cost-efficient pear halo configuration available — a 1ct lab pear in a 91-review halo setting for under $3,000 total.

**$5,000–$8,000 total — Natural Entry**
A 0.75ct natural pear (G VS2, GIA Excellent, ~$2,200–$2,800) + Pavé Diamond Halo Pear in 14K white gold ($1,555) = complete ring $3,755–$4,355. The Halo Magnification Effect delivers a 0.90–0.95ct visual outcome. This is the sweet-spot budget for natural pear halo rings — you achieve the 1ct+ visual appearance at sub-1ct stone cost, with 91 buyer-confirmed setting quality.

**$8,000–$12,000 total — 1ct Natural**
A 1.00ct natural pear (G VS2, GIA Excellent, ~$3,500–$4,500) + Classic Halo in 14K rose gold ($2,300, 39 reviews) = complete ring $5,800–$6,800. Or: 1.00ct pear + Blue Nile Studio Heiress Halo in platinum ($3,585, 41 reviews) = $7,085–$8,085. This tier delivers a full-carat natural pear in a buyer-confirmed, well-reviewed setting at a price that includes both excellent stone quality and setting design.

**$12,000–$20,000 total — Statement**
A 1.50ct natural pear (G VS2, GIA Excellent, ~$7,000–$9,500) + Round Split Band Halo in 14K rose gold ($4,400, 210 reviews) = complete ring $11,400–$13,900. The 210-review Round Split Band setting at this stone size creates a fully elaborated statement ring with accent diamonds running down the split shank. Or: 1.50ct pear + Double Halo Gala ($5,985, 11 reviews) = $12,985–$15,485. Maximum visual impact at this budget tier.

