>
> The two things I look for when auditing a pear halo beyond The Halo Continuity Rule are the gap width between center stone and halo, and the accent diamond color. Both are visible in Blue Nile's 360° video. A halo that fits beautifully in a still photo can show a disconnected floating ring in video — watch the gap while the ring rotates. A center stone that looks white in isolation can look warm inside an F-color accent ring if there is even a one-grade color mismatch. These are not hypothetical concerns — they are the two reasons I see most often behind pear halo ring returns and resets. Get these right and the halo pear ring category is the best value per visual dollar in engagement jewelry." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

